rectly, though I notice the RST markup syntax for download links is included literally in the knowledge file rather than being converted to a more neutral format. The core technical details about Java, Maven, and the required JAR files are all accurate though, so this is more of a formatting inconsistency than a factual error. The next steps match up between the source and knowledge base — selecting the external program radio button and browse button is consistent, and the file selection for Windows versus Linux is accurate, though the knowledge base uses RST formatting for the download link while the source keeps it simpler.\n\nFor step 4, the paraphrase is solid — right-clicking an HTML file in Eclipse's package explorer and selecting \"open with httpDump\" to launch the tool captures the original meaning well, even if minor details like \"等\" were simplified.\n\nNow I'm checking whether any fabrications were introduced. The \"モジュール\" label in step 1 appears to be an addition not present in the source material.\n\nLooking at step 3 more closely, the Windows download link for httpDump.bat is preserved with RST markup intact, which isn't ideal for a knowledge file but doesn't misrepresent the actual content. The source material for the delivery method section seems to be cut off mid-sentence, so I can't fully verify that section against the original. Looking at the RST structure more carefully, I can see the document uses equals signs for the main title and the top-level sections, then dashes for subsections underneath. The hierarchy shows \"リクエスト単体データ作成ツール インストールガイド\" as the main title, followed by sections like 前提事項, 提供方法, and Eclipseとの連携, with nested subsections like 設定画面起動 and 外部プログラム選択 underneath those.\n\nThe knowledge base split this into 4 sections, combining the first three headings into s1 and then breaking out the remaining subsections individually. The real problem is that s1's title \"設定画面起動\" doesn't accurately reflect that it's actually bundling toget